[{"sha":"bc586898830e0459f0f533a76d7a94c09582255a","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"terminal: StreamsForTesting helper

This is to allow convenient testing of functions that are designed to work
directly with *terminal.Streams or the individual stream objects inside.

Because the InputStream and OutputStream APIs expose directly an *os.File,
this does some extra work to set up OS-level pipes so we can capture the
output into local buffers to make test assertions against. The idea here
is to keep the tricky stuff we need for testing confined to the test
codepaths, so that the "real" codepaths don't end up needing to work
around abstractions that are otherwise unnecessary.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/bc586898830e0459f0f533a76d7a94c09582255a"},{"sha":"ee78ac6de161962e02fa2daf4e2b86891623ba95","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ee78ac6de161962e02fa2daf4e2b86891623ba95"},{"sha":"0ec7bbadb9701382ee9aeebdac86cf1b69944f38","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Initial stubbing of the "terraform test" experimental command","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0ec7bbadb9701382ee9aeebdac86cf1b69944f38"}]

[{"sha":"cf4b7ad67524c4a27ba38b6ac2c746aa9d677960","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Add initial command views abstraction

Terraform supports multiple output formats for several sub-commands.
The default format is user-readable text, but many sub-commands support
a `-json` flag to output a machine-readable format for the result. The
output command also supports a `-raw` flag for a simpler, scripting-
focused machine readable format.

This commit adds a "views" abstraction, intended to help ensure
consistency between the various output formats. This extracts the render
specific code from the command package, and moves it into a views
package. Each command is expected to create an interface for its view,
and one or more implementations of that interface.

By doing so, we separate the concerns of generating the sub-command
result from rendering the result in the specified output format. This

[{"sha":"a1cfc9d515e282e82f26b8178a26e7d19b35986d","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"terminal: StreamsForTesting helper

This is to allow convenient testing of functions that are designed to work
directly with *terminal.Streams or the individual stream objects inside.

Because the InputStream and OutputStream APIs expose directly an *os.File,
this does some extra work to set up OS-level pipes so we can capture the
output into local buffers to make test assertions against. The idea here
is to keep the tricky stuff we need for testing confined to the test
codepaths, so that the "real" codepaths don't end up needing to work
around abstractions that are otherwise unnecessary.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/a1cfc9d515e282e82f26b8178a26e7d19b35986d"},{"sha":"8c51001fee7d70fbe6a3cfb734a2c23316600e3a","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8c51001fee7d70fbe6a3cfb734a2c23316600e3a"},{"sha":"fb6644c6ef3db27f1c4445023d9e4182b8175f8e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Initial stubbing of the "terraform test" experimental command","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/fb6644c6ef3db27f1c4445023d9e4182b8175f8e"}]

[{"sha":"6d24ecfdcc166f1fdec20009931c8650a6f27de8","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Invert the meaning of xla::Permute, add an inverse xla::PermuteInverse().

Also swap its arguments; to my eyes the call is more natural with the permutation second.

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat
empty strings as null strings within set objects to avoid the failed

[{"sha":"244ce8fde94ca50fe2df8fcb7ea04ca57bff16b4","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Add initial command views abstraction

Terraform supports multiple output formats for several sub-commands.
The default format is user-readable text, but many sub-commands support
a `-json` flag to output a machine-readable format for the result. The
output command also supports a `-raw` flag for a simpler, scripting-
focused machine readable format.

This commit adds a "views" abstraction, intended to help ensure
consistency between the various output formats. This extracts the render
specific code from the command package, and moves it into a views
package. Each command is expected to create an interface for its view,
and one or more implementations of that interface.

By doing so, we separate the concerns of generating the sub-command
result from rendering the result in the specified output format. This
should make it easier to ensure that all output formats will be updated
together when changes occur in the result-generating phase.

There are some other consequences of this restructuring:

- Views now directly access the terminal streams, rather than the
  now-redundant cli.Ui instance;
- With the reorganization of commands, parsing CLI arguments is now the
  responsibility of a separate "arguments" package.

For now, views are added only for the output sub-command, as an example.
Because this command uses code which is shared with the apply and
refresh commands, those are also partially updated.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/244ce8fde94ca50fe2df8fcb7ea04ca57bff16b4"}]

This is to allow convenient testing of functions that are designed to work
directly with *terminal.Streams or the individual stream objects inside.

Because the InputStream and OutputStream APIs expose directly an *os.File,
this does some extra work to set up OS-level pipes so we can capture the
output into local buffers to make test assertions against. The idea here
is to keep the tricky stuff we need for testing confined to the test
codepaths, so that the "real" codepaths don't end up needing to work
around abstractions that are otherwise unnecessary.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/0e24b8c022fc2ade691ad2b7cac2154a92dee0f7"}]

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

[{"sha":"9fcf66e16dfbd32ebf739bac3e2dd1db59c67360","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Change xla::IsPermutation() not to check the size, and make its implementation O(n).

xla::IsPermutation() does two things: it checks a permutation is actually a permutation, and checks it has a particular size. There's no need to do the latter in xla::IsPermutation because it can be done just as easily by checking .size(), and a number of callers don't need the size check.

In addition, change the implementation to be O(n) time; there's no need to call std::is_permutation() which guarantees nothing better than O(n^2) behavior.

[{"sha":"ea02dac29d9f10309d813fd038775e64bb70bc21","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Add initial command views abstraction

Terraform supports multiple output formats for several sub-commands.
The default format is user-readable text, but many sub-commands support
a `-json` flag to output a machine-readable format for the result. The
output command also supports a `-raw` flag for a simpler, scripting-
focused machine readable format.

This commit adds a "views" abstraction, intended to help ensure
consistency between the various output formats. This extracts the render
specific code from the command package, and moves it into a views
package. Each command is expected to create an interface for its view,
and one or more implementations of that interface.

By doing so, we separate the concerns of generating the sub-command
result from rendering the result in the specified output format. This
should make it easier to ensure that all output formats will be updated
together when changes occur in the result-generating phase.

There are some other consequences of this restructuring:

- Views now directly access the terminal streams, rather than the
  now-redundant cli.Ui instance;
- With the reorganization of commands, parsing CLI arguments is now the
  responsibility of a separate "arguments" package.

For now, views are added only for the output sub-command, as an example.
Because this command uses code which is shared with the apply and
refresh commands, those are also partially updated.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ea02dac29d9f10309d813fd038775e64bb70bc21"}]

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was
being lost.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e"},{"sha":"98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26606 from hashicorp/jbardin/proposed-set-comparison

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"}]

[{"sha":"ffba8064edb6c56f0106638026859b9f2e8ce579","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"terminal: StreamsForTesting helper

This is to allow convenient testing of functions that are designed to work
directly with *terminal.Streams or the individual stream objects inside.

Because the InputStream and OutputStream APIs expose directly an *os.File,
this does some extra work to set up OS-level pipes so we can capture the
output into local buffers to make test assertions against. The idea here
is to keep the tricky stuff we need for testing confined to the test
codepaths, so that the "real" codepaths don't end up needing to work
around abstractions that are otherwise unnecessary.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/ffba8064edb6c56f0106638026859b9f2e8ce579"}]
